entry.title: [iOS] Ensures test fails gracefully if cookies are not available
entry.content:
When a test suite is executed, it should be able to run each tests,

even the tests that fails. This means that no test should cause the

program to halt, because of CHECK or of invalid memory.



Earl-grey tests do not stop when an assertion fails. This means that

we can not protect CHECK and memory using EG assertions. The test

will fail but the code should either ensure the run ends or allows the

test to go on as much as possible.



The method to retrieve cookies in earl-grey failed with a DCHECK after

an assertion. This CL ensures that the assertion is logged as failing,

but, instead of triggering a DCHECK, the method returns nil.



Since on objective-C any method can be call on nil, this will not

cause the test to crash later.



Fixed: 1510325

entry.content:
The update is pushed in the vector after the penalty check.

entry.title: WebNN: Fix UBSan failure for XNNPACK reshape to scalar test case
entry.content:
When XNNPACK backend reshapes to 0-D scalar where the new shape is

empty, there is an UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer (UBSan) failure, for

example [1]. The previous implementation uses a `WTF::Vector` to

represent the new shape. `WTF::Vector` doesn’t allocate a buffer for an

empty vector. That causes `new_shape.data()` to return nullptr which is

passed to XNNPACK and used as the source address for `memcpy`.



This CL fixes this issue by using a stack-allocated array to represent

the new shape instead. Its address would be valid even when the array is

empty.



[1]: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/linux-ubsan-fyi-rel/1272/test-results?sortby=&groupby=&q=xnnpack

entry.title: device selection: Do not special case multi-node changes
entry.content:
Merge the logic of HandleHotPlugDevice and HandleNonHotplugNodesChange:

When multiple audio devices are plugged, treat as if they are plugged

one by one. The device selection algorithm is expected to handle

scenarios like this well. This would also be more robust on reboots,

where it is likely not all audio devices are probed at once and

SwitchToPreviousActiveDeviceIfAvailable cannot work reliably.



Test fixes:

- The new algorithm expects the active device has the highest

priority among all connected devices for restoration to work.

Update SetupCrasAudioHandlerWithActiveNodeInPref to set the

user priority.

- Remove uses of kHeadphone. It is special cased to always be

selected when plugged.

- Explicitly set the active device in

ChangeOutputVolumeFromNonChromeSourceNonActiveDevice.

entry.title: [LineBreaker] Support rewinding floats in `nowrap`
entry.content:
This patch supports rewinding floats in `nowrap` or `pre`.



In Blink, when NG was first implemented, rewinding floats

was harder, as it had separated lists for floats. So rewinding

stopped at the last float. This wasn't really correct, but it

passed all existing tests.



This patch changes `Rewind()` to actually rewind positioned

floats when necessary.



The spec isn't very clear about this case. When Gecko fixed

their reported cases 5 years ago[1], they filed a spec

issue[2] and added several tests[3].



This patch changes the rendering of `float-nowrap-4.html`, one

of the tests by Mozilla, so this patch adds a new reference.

PS18 can fix this issue without changing the behavior for

`float-nowrap-4.html`, but logically speaking, this behavior

looks more correct.



The change is under a runtime flag `RewindFloats`, enabled by

default as a kill-switch in case this change turned out to be

not web-compatible.



[1] https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=488725#c38

[2] https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/3038

[3] https://wpt.fyi/results/css/CSS2/floats?label=master&label=experimental&aligned&q=float-nowrap-



Bug: 1499290
